betterquesting:10.desc:8: Iron, one of the simplest metals. It was deposited here by meteorites in the form of iron ore. Hidden among the regolith, I found the iron. I think I should be able to smelt this in order to form some kind of ingot. This will restart the industrial revolution.

I should aim to get copper next. It is a orange metal with superb thermal and electrical conductivity. These ember crystals I am getting from the void may be able to transform iron into this. It will require a lot of force which I shall exert using a hammer. Copper, a metal forged in the heart of ember. This shall be used for all of my electrical applications.
Andesite seems to contain small traces of tin. Melting the andesite with a special apparatus wiil probably allow me to extract this tin and stamp it to form my first ingot.

A metal with an incredibly high density and low melting point, making it ideal for many of my future endeavours. It seems that the embered cinders can be infused into stone and melted down into a liquid with similar properties as lead. Mixing these molten cinders with a easily mixable metal will allow me to form lead.

I was placing my clay near some sand and I found out when they mix they create a weird mixture maybe I can use it to craft a sort of brick

and I wonder what are those golems that I have been seeing maybe I should defeat some of them aswell I might get something useful...

We will see...

Embers are an ancient limited resource that seem to able to power many of the primitive machines I may need to use. The ember bore is a device used to extract ember from the endless void, powered by fuels similar to the furnace. However, it may prove ineffective at high altitudes such as y-levels above 7. Any ember that is extracted will coalesce if in a mechanical core for long enough. I can also use another mechanical core to allow myself to insert and extract materials to and from it.

Copper seems to glow brighter when there is an increased ember aura. I may be able to create something like a compass or even better, a gauge, that will help me find out which areas are better for ember extraction.

Caminite Bricks seem to be very useful. I should be able to make some sort of pipes in order to move items between locations. Caminite can also probably be used for levers if shaped properly. These levers wil be able to power a gear, causing it to turn and extracting items. Archaic Bricks from the golems will help improve the structural integrity of the pipes as well.

The Wooden Furnace that I have been using is becoming extremely tedious. I need to constantly put out the fires that threaten to burn the furnace. Caminite Bricks are able to absorb heat quite well and together with some stone, I will be able to make an improved furnace. This furnace should also be about twice as quick as my old furnace due to its higher heat retention.

Well finally I can start grinding Lets see....
Cobblestone is made out of pebbles if I grind it I might get gravel and grinding gravel might give sand! 
Grinding Wheat would give flour I can use it for food chaff would be useful aswell
and I can get sawdust by grinding Logs!
The quern is heavier than I thought I cant move it I need to make a crank to move it.

§l§rI had an idea all of the sudden I am thinking of a machine in my head if I could use the irons I smelted in order to make a blade with it
And if I could support it with some stone I can make a primal machine to grind things but it would be manuel its better than nothing I guess

§lInfo§r: Quern drops the items from the opening at the front of it. You can place a chest there to automatically extract the outputs.
§l

I am getting bored of using that manual hand crank. I thought of a design for a windmill that would rotate with the power of the wind and has an axle that is connected to a gear. With this, I will be able to automate the wooden mechanical hopper and the quern. 

This design is so effective it can even work when facing the sky or the void. I also left some empty spots for new blades which will allow it to catch more wind but also slow the windmill slightly due to their weight. 

The wind is always changing and it seems that rain and thunderstorms cause it to spin up to 2 and 3 times faster respectively. However, this wind value seems to constantly be changing even within the same weather.

I can't put items into the quern directly with my hands for it may crush my fingers. This is too risky. I have planned a primitive hopper that will input items into it. However, it will require me to manually power it.

§lINFO:§r You can Shift + RightClick to rotate the input side of the hopper you need to put a chest on the input side and you need a crank on the sides."

The windmill doesn't seem to keep up with my requirement for mechanical power but I can't add any more blades to this existing design. I dont know.... What if I make the blades bigger...

§§§lI got an amazing idea!§r § I will make the blades bigger so they would can produce more mechanical power. However, this will limit the number of blades I can place on it. By my calculations, I will be able to place only 4 extra blades on it.

With the atmospheric gauge, I am able to check where the ember aura is the highest. I need to be sure that I place it in the best chunk to maximise my ember extraction.
I expected to see the ember in its raw form but... they seem to have crystallised into crystals, shards and grit. These may be less powerful but this is the only way I can harness them for now.
